            "answer_text": "Yes. Soviet-style command economy is a baby of the Marxist concept of class struggle and radical social transformation. Which is why it\u2019s always a mobilization economy. The needs of the military-industrial complex and secret services are always at the center of it, because the surrounding Capitalists will always make mischief and seek its destruction. Which is why Stalinist societies boast much shorter adaptation cycles to wartime economy in comparison to market-based ones. This is the main enduring advantage of Socialism before Capitalism: during the periods of great struggle\u2014wars, pestilence, asteroid hits, pandemics\u2014it can very fast adapt to the changed situation and the character of new threats. As an example, an investment project for anything more substantial than a cowshed in the Soviet Union always needed to be signed off by government functionaries not only for its fire safety, compliance with sanitary norms and suchlike, but also for being compliant with local and national \u201cmobilization plans\u201d\u2014i.e. how exactly the building can be requisitioned for war purposes and in which time frame the moment the D-day arrives. In 1941, the Soviet government managed within weeks to disassemble, move to the east, re-assemble and put into use thousands of military plants and production units, well away from the fast advancing German troops. For comparison, it took almost two years for the USA, who not even were under an attack, to deploy the industrial infrastructure for war deliveries to Europe under the contracts received ahead of WW2.  Below, a Soviet poster \u201cIf war happens tomorrow\u201d It expresses the spirit of a \u201ctotal war\u201d (as in \u201cWollt ihr den totalen Krieg? Wollt ihr ihn, wenn n\u00f6tig, totaler und radikaler, als wir ihn uns heute \u00fcberhaupt erst vorstellen k\u00f6nnen?\u201d) that permeated not only the military planning, but other central aspects of Stalinist society. The Soviet mobpl\u00e1ns (\u201cmobilization plans\u201d) always pertained to the most protected state secrets. Enough to say, there remained close to none photographs of equipment being relocated east in 1941\u201342 (here\u2019s one). If you were found with a camera in a vicinity of a railway station back then, you would face an immediate arrest with a very harsh interrogation to follow. Still, \u201ceveryone\u201d in the USSR knew for certain that for example our plants producing cigarettes and pasta could switch to making rifle rounds on a dime. (As a matter of fact, they couldn\u2019t. Yet, some of the equipment could be repossessed for war production indeed. And as a matter of fact, our tractor plants were designed with production capacity 100% adaptable to making tanks).  ",
