            "answer_text": "It does in a time of crisis or time when decisions need to be made quickly. It can devote society\u2019s resources to a single goal and ensure that that goal is just about everyone\u2019s goal. Less time and effort are dedicated to \u201cnon-essential\u201d activities. The Soviet Union put a satellite into earth orbit before the U.S. did because of a single-minded effort to do so, dictated and enforced from the top. While Russian leadership was driving towards a specific goal with laser-like focus, the U.S. was making cars, refrigerators and suburban subdivisions. There was zero leadership interest in making satellites - the U.S. allowed the Army and Navy compete for the honor of being the second people to put a satellite into orbit. In fact, the Navy had been given the go-ahead and the Army was not given first shot. Navy liquid-fueled rockets blew up spectacularly on the launching pad, or malfunctioned equally spectacularly a few seconds into flight. The Army\u2019s solid fuel rocket finally launched the second man-made satellite into space, and the Russians won the satellite race. They also won the race to orbit a man in space, and followed up by putting the world\u2019s first woman into space. But the U.S. landed men on the moon and the Russians were never really in that race as successfully as the Americans. Why? Because when a market-oriented multi-polar society decides on a single goal - land a man on the moon and return him safely to Earth - it can do things rapidly and flexibly. I noted that another poster sang the glories of centrally planning what people want, without figuring out just how you determine what they want. Usually it ends up being what the planners want for the people, and screw what the people might actually want. Case in point: in the old Soviet Union, birth control pills and devices were not in the planners\u2019 vision of what Soviet women needed. So when Irina was pregnant and didn\u2019t want to deliver little Svetlana, she had to go to a state abortion clinic. That was her birth control option. As a result, Russian abortion rates were significantly higher than rates in the rest of Europe. BTW - Russian had been struggling with low birth rates for a long time. Repeated abortions can make a woman infertile - a bad thing if you want to boost population. D\u2019oh! After the fall of the Soviet Union, birth control pills and other contraceptive methods became available because of consumer choice. Russian abortion rates declined to match those of the rest of Europe. Irina, it seems, didn\u2019t want to abort Svetlana; she wanted never to conceive her. But centralized planning is absolutely the best. Screw Irina. The state knows better. ",
